<subSubSection id="C30EB4BB83717E0EA390FE66B72C6FD7" pageId="7" pageNumber="218" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BABE73083717E0EA390FE66B72C6FD7" blockId="7.[151,1437,150,681]" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283717E0EA390FE66B7066F67" bold="true" box="[199,315,511,537]" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383717E0EA1B5FE66B55A6F67" authorityName="G. Q. Liu &amp; Q. Liu" authorityYear="1998" box="[738,871,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutulus">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283717E0EA1B5FE66B55A6F67" box="[738,871,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">M. acutulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in body color, surface, and vestiture, and the posterolateral angles of the pronotum. The two species can be separated from each other by the following differences: 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383717E0EA3C0FDDEB7086F1E" baseAuthorityName="Stal" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[151,309,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornaticeps">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283717E0EA3C0FDDEB7086F1E" box="[151,309,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">M. ornaticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is relatively larger than 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383717E0EA106FDDEB4E56F1F" authorityName="G. Q. Liu &amp; Q. Liu" authorityYear="1998" box="[593,728,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutulus">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283717E0EA106FDDEB4E56F1F" box="[593,728,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">M. acutulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the light-colored spots on the forewings are larger and more conspicuous in 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383717E0EA21DFDF2B7DA6FFA" baseAuthorityName="Stal" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[330,487,619,644]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornaticeps">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283717E0EA21DFDF2B7DA6FFA" box="[330,487,619,644]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">M. ornaticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383717E0EA11FFDF2B4F26FFB" authorityName="G. Q. Liu &amp; Q. Liu" authorityYear="1998" box="[584,719,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutulus">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283717E0EA11FFDF2B4F26FFB" box="[584,719,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">M. acutulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the genital capsule and parameres are also different from each other.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
